    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:8bfa09ad-e509-41f7-8e25-a144593417f5",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 9-year-old girl who looks tired and uncomfortable, sitting curled slightly forward on the exam table and swallowing carefully because of throat pain. Her cheeks are flushed from fever, her voice is muffled and soft, and she winces when trying to drink water. On examination she has enlarged erythematous tonsils with patchy white exudate, tender anterior cervical lymph nodes, and mild halitosis. She has had 2 days of worsening sore throat, fever, painful swallowing, reduced appetite, and less interest in her usual play.\n\nShe lives with her mother, father, and older brother in a suburban neighborhood and is in primary school. Normally, {patientName} is energetic, social, and talkative, enjoying drawing, playground games, and reading illustrated adventure books. Over the last two days she has stayed home from school, spent more time resting on the couch, and has been asking for cold drinks and popsicles because warm foods make her throat hurt more.\n\nHer family describes her as generally healthy and active, with no chronic medical conditions. She participates in school activities and usually sleeps well, though the current illness has caused restless sleep and nighttime complaints of throat pain. She has had no breathing difficulty, drooling, or neck stiffness, but her parents are worried because her fever and throat pain increased quickly.\n\nAt home, the family is attentive and supportive, alternating fluids, soft foods, and fever medicine. There are several recent sore-throat illnesses reported among classmates at school. {patientName} is shy with new clinicians but becomes more cooperative when her mother stays nearby and explanations are simple and reassuring."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:5ebb39f8-bd2c-4e28-b346-a175ef5869f8",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no known chronic cardiopulmonary, renal, or neurologic disease and is up to date on routine childhood immunizations. She has no prior hospitalizations and no history of recurrent peritonsillar abscess. Past illnesses have been limited to typical childhood viral upper respiratory infections. She has not had recent international travel or known exposure to tobacco smoke at home.\n\nFor the current illness, symptoms began about 48 hours ago with sore throat and low appetite, followed by fever, more painful swallowing, and reduced energy. Her parents report decreased solid food intake but she is still able to sip fluids. There is no significant cough, which increases suspicion for streptococcal pharyngotonsillitis. She has had no rash, vomiting, or shortness of breath. The family has given weight-appropriate acetaminophen at home with partial fever relief."
          }
        ]
      }
